snippet.textDisplay: I said this on another clip of this show, and I'll say it again: what conceivable reason is/was the owner doing this? It doesn't save money on product used (intentionally cooking for the next day means you're buying the same amount of product), it takes more manpower to package then freeze then defrost, and it makes for worse tasting food at the end! It's not even lazy, it's overly complicated and wasting money!
snippet.textOriginal: I said this on another clip of this show, and I'll say it again: what conceivable reason is/was the owner doing this? snippet.textDisplay: Please come to Mobile, Alabama. This same scenario and  sometimes worse is common for many in the food industry.  There are four to five restaurants within a mile/mile and a half radius of each other;  so it is very easy to see the inappropriate procedures/operations.  Believe it or not,  I was constantly scrutinized for habitually following the rules and would get this common statement, "It does take all of that".  Fashion trends have downplayed and made many food safety guidelines obsolete and only followed if caught.  The minimum mentality,  and management by "only serious crisis" is alive and well.
